In this episode of The Simpsons we follow Homer and the reunion of his Mother Mona. After learning that Mr. Burns wants his employees to clean litter from a highway maintained by his company on a Saturday, Homer fakes his own death using a dummy to avoid it. When Marge discovers his scheme the next day, she makes Homer go to the Springfield Hall of Records to explain he is not dead. Afterwards he sees in the record that his mother is still alive. unconvinced, he goes to his mother's grave and discovers that it is actually someones elses. Nearby, homer sees his own grave and falls into it. Homer is approached by a woman who chastises him for falling into her son's grave. Homer recognizes her as his mother Mona, and both embrace each other. He takes her home to meet the family. She also bonds with Lisa, being on the same intellectual level and of the same socially-conscious personality. However, a police car drives by and Mona runs inside the house, making Lisa a little suspicious. The family confronts Mona, who reveals the truth about her past. In 1969, Mona joined a group of hippies to protest a germ warfare laboratory owned by Mr. Burns, which was preparing to poison everyone in Springfield. The group detonated an "antibiotic bomb" inside the lab, killing all the germs. Mr. Burns was trampled by the crew while attempting to stop them. When Mona went back to help Burns, she was recognized as one of the perpetrators, forcing her to leave Homer and go into hiding. Homer then wonders why Mona never contacted him. Mona, insisting that she did send packages, they head to the post office to claim the undelivered packages At the post office, Mr. Burns  recognizes her and calls the FBI. the FBI and Mr. Burns tracks her down back to the Simpsons house and Homer helps Mona escape. Mona realizes that now she must go into hiding leaving Homer  once more. This time, Homer gets to say goodbye to his mother, but it's clear that the pain of her absence will remain. Homer sadly tells his mother to not forget him, and she replies that he will always be a part of her. With Mona driving away, Homer waves into the distance, Homer sits alone on his car and watches the stars into the night as the credits roll.

Happy holidays. â¤ï¸ Three weeks ago, when the vet told me we should probably stop trying to cast Backspace's foot, I felt very resigned. Despite exercises and 4 different casts, his leg continued to stick out behind him when he walked. It was straighter and more flexible, but he just couldn't get into the habit of putting it in front of him. I've worked 10 hour days every day since November and I felt lousy about the fact that I couldn't devote more time to physical therapy now that the cast had failed. Thinking about his leg occupied so much space in my mind because even if the vets said it was time to let it go, I couldn't. I figured that since he's such an easy going kitten and if he was going to lose the leg anyway, perhaps there was no harm in trying a homemade splint. I knew I wanted to keep the toes exposed and to add a curve to his hock. I thought if the splint was very minimal, he'd be more inclined to try to use it so I bought a set of finger splints and cut them to size.  The first prototype I made had a part sticking out the back that made it uncomfortable for him to lift up his leg behind him like he normally did when he walked so he stopped doing that almost immediately. Within days, he started to walk with that foot pointing forward. It's been almost two weeks and his leg has improved drastically. And while Backspace still limps a little and he doesn't always use that leg when he runs, it's clear that it isn't getting in the way like it used to. So the leg may not be perfect, but it's functional and I think it'll just keep getting better with time. I showed our vet a video 3 days after this first splint and she was delighted and fully on board with continuing. She said that she really enjoys seeing how creative rescues can be when working around their limited resources. We learn to make do with what we have and in this case, it meant that after trying a traditional strategy, we went completely homemade and it worked despite our expectations. So for this holiday season, not only does Backspace get to keep his leg, but I got a helpful reminder sometimes, it just takes a little creativity and a change in perspective to get a different outcome. Thank you for your support and I can't wait for you to hear our big news for 2024. @Meow Parlour #kitten #backspace #twistedlegsyndrome #christmasmiracle
